Almost 200,000 Scots aged 16 to 74 had never worked or were long-term unemployed at the time of the last census three years ago. Census reveals 5% of Scots never had a job or without work Almost 200,000 Scots aged 16 to 74 had never worked or were long-term unemployed at the time of the last census three years ago.The 198,630 people who had never had a job or who had last worked in 2009 or earlier represented 5% of the Scottish population in 2011.More than half (51%) held no qualifications, falling to a third (33%) of those aged 16 to 24.Young people were most likely to be out of work, with the proportion of people in the category falling from 8% in the 16 to 24 age group to 4% of those aged 50 to 64.Women made up the largest grouping, with 102,667 never having worked or long-term unemployed, compared to 95,963 men.Glasgow had the highest number of people in the category (41,472), followed by Edinburgh (15,648) and North Lanarkshire (15,078).Dundee had 7,205 people who had never worked or were long-term unemployed, compared to Aberdeen's 5,340.The islands were the least likely to have high numbers of people who had never worked or were long-term unemployed, with 320 falling into the category in Shetland, 361 in Orkney and 644 in the Western Isles.At the time of the 2011 census, 20% of the four million people aged 16 to 74 in Scotland had lower managerial, administrative and professional jobs, the largest socio-economic grouping.Small employers and own account workers made up 7% of the population while 9% held higher managerial, administrative and professional jobs. 